#compdef sonnerie
# =============================================================================
# sonnerie — Charles Samuels's "simple timeseries database" — a
#            Rust embedded timeseries database with a CLI for
#            ingesting + querying + compacting time-keyed records.
#            Distinguishing from InfluxDB, TimescaleDB, Prometheus,
#            VictoriaMetrics, and other timeseries databases by:
#              - EMBEDDED + FILE-BASED — sonnerie is not a server;
#                it's an embedded database that operates on local
#                files in a directory (no daemon, no network port)
#              - APPEND-ONLY + COMPACTION — new records are written
#                to transaction files; periodic `compact` operations
#                merge transactions into the main database file +
#                purge deleted records
#              - MAJOR vs MINOR COMPACTION via `--major` / `-M` —
#                full database rewrite for maximum compression vs
#                incremental transaction merging
#              - GEGNUM (Icelandic for "through") TRANSFORMATION —
#                `--gegnum <cmd>` pipes the entire database
#                through an external command during compaction;
#                useful for bulk schema migrations or value
#                rewrites
#              - STRFTIME-DRIVEN TIMESTAMPS — `--timestamp-format
#                "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f"` converts ISO-8601 input
#                to nanosecond Unix timestamps via chrono's
#                NaiveDateTime parser
#              - WILDCARD KEY FILTERING — `%` is the wildcard in
#                `read "metric.%"` style queries; `sonnerie read
#                "cpu.host%"` selects all hosts under cpu.*
#              - TIME-RANGE QUERIES — --after-time / --before-time
#                / --time use EasyNaiveDateTime (chrono-driven)
#                parser accepting ISO-9601 date / seconds /
#                nanosecond precision
#              - RAYON-PARALLELIZED — uses rayon for parallel
#                segment processing during reads + compactions
#              - 4 SUBCOMMANDS: add (ingest records) / delete
#                (remove by key or time) / compact (merge
#                transactions) / read (query records)
#            Used by: small-scale timeseries logging where running
#            InfluxDB/Prometheus is overkill, embedded device
#            telemetry, custom monitoring pipelines, and as a
#            reference implementation of chrono + clap-derive +
#            rayon Rust CLI design.
#
# Author:  Charles Samuels (njaard on GitHub) — Estonian software
#          engineer.  sonnerie released ~2017; active development
#          through 2026 with regular releases.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/njaard/sonnerie
#          https://github.com/njaard/sonnerie/blob/master/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/njaard/sonnerie/blob/master/Cargo.toml
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses clap 4.x derive (`#[derive(Parser,
#          Subcommand)]`) with 4 subcommands + chrono-driven
#          timestamp parsing.  Headline library: **chrono**
#          (clap is well-documented; chrono is the new variant
#          being documented here, opening Axis 15).
# Library: chrono (https://github.com/chronotope/chrono)
#          ("chrono" — Kang Seonghoon (lifthrasiir on GitHub,
#           original author since 2014) + chronotope organization
#           (current maintainers) — released 2014 as "Date and
#           time library for Rust".  Distinct from every
#           previously-documented Rust library by being narrowly
#           focused on COMPREHENSIVE DATE + TIME ARITHMETIC +
#           PARSING + FORMATTING + TIMEZONES:
#             1. DATETIME + DATE + TIME + DURATION TYPES — chrono
#                ships a hierarchy of date/time types covering
#                every common use case:
#                  - NaiveDate     — date without timezone (2026-06-01)
#                  - NaiveTime     — time without timezone (14:32:18.123)
#                  - NaiveDateTime — datetime without timezone
#                  - DateTime<Tz>  — datetime with timezone (DateTime<Utc>,
#                                     DateTime<Local>, DateTime<FixedOffset>)
#                  - Duration       — signed nanosecond-precision duration
#                  - TimeDelta      — alias for Duration
#                  - Months         — for month-level arithmetic
#                  - Days           — for day-level arithmetic
#             2. STRFTIME-COMPATIBLE FORMATTING — chrono supports
#                the FULL strftime format string dialect
#                (matching POSIX strftime + GNU extensions):
#                  - %Y / %y / %m / %d / %H / %M / %S / %f / %z /
#                    %Z / %A / %a / %B / %b / %j / %V / %u / %w /
#                    %p / %P / %s / %T / %F / %D / %R / %r / %t /
#                    %% / + GNU extensions
#                Same format strings work for FORMATTING + PARSING
#                via NaiveDateTime::parse_from_str
#             3. TIMEZONE SUPPORT via chrono-tz feature — full
#                IANA timezone database (tz database) integration
#                with chrono-tz companion crate:
#                  let ny: DateTime<Tz> = Tz::America__New_York
#                      .with_ymd_and_hms(2026, 6, 1, 14, 32, 18)
#                      .unwrap();
#             4. SERDE INTEGRATION via "serde" feature — chrono's
#                NaiveDateTime + DateTime<Utc> + Duration
#                serialize/deserialize as RFC 3339 strings
#                + ISO 8601 by default
#             5. ARITHMETIC OPERATIONS — Duration + DateTime
#                arithmetic via std::ops::Add/Sub + checked_add
#                /checked_sub variants:
#                  let tomorrow = now + Duration::days(1);
#                  let next_year = now.checked_add_months(Months::new(12))?;
#             6. RELATIVE-TIME via humantime/chrono-humanize —
#                Charles Samuels (also author of sonnerie) +
#                others built chrono-humanize for "3 days ago"-
#                style relative time output (different from
#                humantime R621 which targets parsing rather
#                than display)
#             7. DEPRECATED-LEAP-SECOND MODELING — chrono
#                explicitly distinguishes IANA-tracked leap
#                seconds from UTC seconds; the few documented
#                Rust apps that need leap-second-correctness
#                (astronomy, GPS) use chrono's leap-second-aware
#                comparators)
# License: MIT (sonnerie); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (chrono)
# Status:  sonnerie — 278+ stars on njaard/sonnerie, used in
#          niche timeseries-logging applications; chrono —
#          3,862+ stars on chronotope/chrono, ~900M crates.io
#          downloads (TOP-15 Rust crate by download volume),
#          foundational dependency of basically every Rust CLI
#          + server that touches dates/times, including: rbspy
#          (Ruby sampling profiler, 2.5k stars), getsentry/edmg
#          util, dhth/tomo, phip1611/gitlab-timelogs, Quesys-tech/
#          vrcwatch.rs, TimmyOVO/freshrss-filter + thousands of
#          Rust applications.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 69 +
#                                                  AXIS 15 (DATE/TIME) OPENS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 69TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 68 to 69 documented
# libraries (chrono via sonnerie).  Rust **breaks the third triple-tie
# at 68** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=68 since R643) to take SOLO LEAD at 69.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=69, Go=68, TypeScript-Node=68 (Rust SOLO at 69,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 68 — twenty-third time Rust has taken solo lead in
# this round-sequence; FIRST time any language crosses 69).  Taxonomy
# now spans 384 cross-language CLI library variants across 93 documented
# languages.
#
# Pattern: R644 93rd language (Slang) → R645 Rust=69 (chrono THIS —
# Axis 15 OPENS) → expected R646 Go=69 → expected R647 TS-Node=69 →
# expected R648 94th language.  This is the 1st of 3 leader bumps in
# the new segment.
#
# **MAJOR MILESTONE: AXIS 15 (DATE / TIME) OPENS**
#
# With R645, **Axis 15 (DATE / TIME)** opens as the fifteenth axis in
# the cross-language CLI library taxonomy.  Prior to R645 the
# documented axes were:
#   - Axis 1:  ARGUMENT PARSING
#   - Axis 4:  COLOR/STYLING
#   - Axis 5:  PROGRESS/SPINNERS
#   - Axis 6:  ERROR DIAGNOSTICS (Rust=6, deepest)
#   - Axis 7:  BOX DRAWING / DECORATION
#   - Axis 8:  INTERACTIVE PROMPTS
#   - Axis 9:  UNIFIED LOGGING (6/6/6 three-way symmetric)
#   - Axis 10: TABLES / TABULAR OUTPUT (2/2/2 symmetric)
#   - Axis 11: HUMANIZATION (1/1/1 symmetric)
#   - Axis 12: TEXT WRAPPING & FORMATTING (1/1/1 symmetric)
#   - Axis 13: CONFIGURATION FILES (2/2/2 symmetric)
#   - Axis 14: PATHS / FILESYSTEM (2/2/2 symmetric)
#
# Axis 15 (DATE / TIME) captures libraries that handle LOW-LEVEL
# date + time arithmetic + parsing + formatting + timezone handling.
# Distinct from:
#   - Axis 11 (Humanization) which handles "3 days ago" style HUMAN-
#     FRIENDLY formatting of durations + timestamps
#   - Stdlib date/time primitives (std::time / time stdlib / Date) —
#     Axis 15 captures libraries that EXTEND or improve on stdlib
#     semantics
#
# The distinction is sharp: humantime (R621, Axis 11) parses + formats
# durations like "1h 30m"; chrono (R645 THIS, Axis 15) provides full
# Datetime arithmetic + timezone handling + strftime formatting.
# Both are about TIME but at different abstraction levels.
#
# Cross-language Axis 15 prospects for future rounds (NOT yet
# documented):
#   - Rust: jiff (Burntsushi's modern alternative), time-rs (the time
#            crate), speedate
#   - Go: time stdlib (foundational), Go modules like Karrick/tparse
#          for relative-time parsing, jinzhu/now for sugary helpers
#   - Node: date-fns (modular functions), dayjs (lightweight),
#           luxon (immutable + i18n), moment.js (legacy), Temporal
#           proposal polyfill
#   - Python: arrow, pendulum, dateutil, pydantic
#
# Future Axis 15 expansion across Rust + Go + TS-Node in upcoming
# rounds will likely bring this axis to multi-variant coverage
# matching the three-language symmetry of Axes 9-14.
#
# (Leaderboard at R645: Rust=69, Go=68, TS-Node=68.  Rust Axis 6 +
# Axis 9 BOTH at 6 variants.  Axis 9 three-way symmetric at 6/6/6.
# Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.  Axes 11 + 12 at 1/1/1.  Axis 15 /
# Date/Time now Rust=1, Go=0, TS-Node=0 — YOUNGEST axis, RUST-ONLY
# at 1 variant.)
